# EliteSeriesPay

EliteSeriesPay is a local web application for managing participants, payments, and budgets of small paid communities.

## Goals

- Build a useful local application.
- Demonstrate clean Java backend development.
- Use Cursor as an assisted development tool, not as an uncontrolled code generator.

## Approved stack

- Java 21
- Spring Boot
- SQLite
- Flyway
- Spring Data JPA
- Thymeleaf
- Bootstrap
- Maven
- JUnit

## Constraints

- Local application only.
- No React.
- No Docker.
- No Kubernetes.
- No PostgreSQL.
- No Kafka or RabbitMQ.
- No cloud services.
- No external authentication.
- No VK API integration in the first version.

## Domain

Main entities:

- Project
- Participant
- Project membership
- Payment
- Application settings

Payment sources:

- VK Donut
- Other

Business rules:

- Participants are global.
- A participant may belong to multiple projects.
- Project membership has status ACTIVE or LEFT.
- Removing a participant from a project means marking membership as LEFT, not deleting the participant.
- Payments may be in RUB, USD, or EUR.
- USD and EUR payments are converted to RUB using an exchange rate.
- The user may override the exchange rate manually.
- Each project has its own episode cost in RUB.
- The application calculates monthly net income and the number of episodes that can be funded.
- VK Donut fee percent is configurable in application settings.
- Default VK Donut fee percent is 10%.
- Changing VK Donut fee percent affects only future payments.
- Each payment stores the fee percent used at creation time.
- Existing payments must not be recalculated when settings change.
- Other payment sources have no automatic fee.
- Financial history should not be physically deleted after payments exist.
- Projects with historical data should be archived rather than deleted.
- Payments should be voided/cancelled rather than deleted once financial history matters.

## Development rules

- Work in small vertical slices.
- Before significant changes, propose a short plan.
- Do not implement multiple large features at once.
- Keep business logic out of controllers.
- Put business rules in services.
- Add tests for calculation logic and business rules.
- Prefer simple, explicit, readable code.
- Do not introduce technologies outside the approved stack.

## Validation rules

- UI forms should use Bean Validation for user input errors.
- Services must protect business invariants and must not rely only on web-layer validation.
- Service exceptions should not depend on web form field names.
- Controllers may translate service exceptions into form errors.

## Code generation rules

- Do not silently remove existing validation, tests, or business rules during refactoring.
- When changing validation behavior, update both service tests and web form handling.
- Keep normalization such as trimming in one place.
- Keep UI text in Russian.